#Text=3. Results
#Text=3.1. On Benchmark Data
#Text=In order to show the effectiveness of the proposed embedding procedure , both of the classification strategies ( -SVM and -SVM ) have been considered .

#Text=The genetic algorithm has been configured as follows : 100 individuals per 100 generations with a strict early-stop criterion if the average fitness function over rd of the total number of generations is less than or equal to , the elitism is set to 10 % of the population , the selection follows the roulette wheel heuristic , the crossover operator generates new offsprings in a scattered fashion and the mutation acts in a flip-the-bit fashion for boolean genes and adds to real-valued genes a random number extracted from a zero-mean Gaussian distribution whose variance shrinks as generations go by .
#Text=The upper and lower bounds for SVMs hyperparameters are by definition , , and has entries in range .
#Text=Two classification systems have been used as competitors :
#Text=The Weighted Jaccard Kernel .
#Text=Originally proposed in Ref . , the Weighted Jaccard Kernel ( WJK ) is an hypergraph kernel working on the top of the simplicial complexes from the underlying graphs .
#Text=As a proper kernel function , WJK performs an implicit embedding procedure towards a possibly infinite-dimensional Hilbert space .

#Text=In synthesis , the WJK between two simplicial complexes , say and , is evaluated as follows : after considering the ’ simplices-of-node-labels ’ rather than the ’ simplices-of-nodes ’ as described in Section 2.2.1 , the set of unique simplices belonging to either or is considered .
#Text=Then , and are transformed in two vectors , say and , by counting the occurrences of simplices in the unique set within the two simplicial complexes .
#Text=Finally , .
#Text=The kernel matrix obtained by evaluating the pairwise weighted Jaccard similarity between any two pairs of simplicial complexes in the available dataset is finally fed to a -SVM .
#Text=GRALG .
#Text=Originally proposed in Ref . and later used in Refs .
#Text=for image classification , GRALG is a Granular Computing-based classification system for graphs .
#Text=Despite the fact that it considers network motifs rather than simplices , it is still based on the same embedding procedure by means of symbolic histograms .
#Text=In synthesis , GRALG extracts network motifs from the training data and runs a clustering procedure on such subgraphs by using a graph edit distance as the core ( dis)similarity measure .
#Text=The medoids ( MinSODs ) of these clusters form the alphabet on top of which the embedding space is built .
#Text=Two genetic algorithms take care of tuning the alphabet synthesis and the feature selection procedure , respectively .
#Text=GRALG , however , suffers from an heavy computational burden which may become unfeasible for large datasets .
#Text=In order to overcome this problem , the random walk-based variant proposed in Ref . has been used .
#Text=Thirty datasets freely available from Ref . have been considered for testing , all of which well suit the classification problem at hand being labelled on nodes with categorical attributes .
#Text=Each dataset has been split into a training set ( ) and test set ( ) in a stratified manner in order to preserve ground-truth labels distribution across the two splits .
#Text=Validation data have been taken from the training set via 5-fold cross-validation .
#Text=For the proposed embedding procedure and WJK , the Clique complex has been used since the underlying 1-skeleton is already available from the considered datasets .
#Text=For GRALG , the maximum motifs size has been set to 5 and , following Ref . , a subsampling rate of has been performed on the training set .

#Text=Alongside GRALG and WJK , the accuracy of the dummy classifier is also included : the latter serves as a baseline solution and quantifies the performance obtained by a purely random decision rule .

#Text=Indeed , the dummy classifier outputs a given label , say with a probability related to the relative frequency of amongst the training patterns and , by definition , does not consider the information carried out by the pattern descriptions ( input domain ) in training data .
